{{Infobox Rockunit | name = Flat Landing Brook Formation | image = | caption = | type = [[Geological formation]] | age = [[Darriwilian]], {{fossil range|466|465}} | period = Darriwilian | prilithology = [[Rhyolite]] flows, hyaloclastics, [[breccia]]s, [[hyalotuff]]s<ref name="QW">[http://www2.gnb.ca/content/gnb/en/departments/erd/energy/content/minerals/content/Tetagouche_UnitDesc.html Tetagouche Group – Unit Descriptions]</ref> | otherlithology = [[Shale]], [[greywacke]], [[siltstone]], [[ironstone|iron formation]], [[tholeiitic basalt]], [[alkali basalt]]<ref name="QW"/> | namedfor = Flat Landing Brook<ref name="AK">[http://dnr-mrn.gnb.ca/Lexicon/Lexicon/Lexicon_View.aspx?UnitId=137 Flat Landing Brook Formation]</ref> | namedby = R.W. Sullivan, 1990; C.R. van Staal ''et al.'', 1990<ref name="AK"/> | region = {{flag|New Brunswick}} | country = {{flag|Canada}} | coordinates = | unitof = Telagouche Group<ref name="QW"/> | subunits = Reids Brook Member, Forthy Mile Brook Member, Roger Brook Member, Moody Brook Member<ref name="AK"/> | underlies = Little River Formation<ref name="QW"/> | overlies = Nepisiguit Falls Formation<ref name="QW"/> | thickness = Unknown<ref name="AK"/> | extent = | area = | map = | map_caption = }}
The '''Flat Landing Brook Formation''' is a [[geological formation]] in [[Gloucester County, New Brunswick|Gloucester County]] of northern [[New Brunswick]], Canada. It consists mostly of [[volcanic rock]]s that were deposited 466&nbsp;to 465&nbsp;million years ago during the [[Darriwilian]] [[stage (stratigraphy)|stage]] of the [[Middle Ordovician]] [[epoch (geology)|epoch]].<ref name="AK"/>
==Lithology== [[Rhyolite]] flows, [[breccia]]s and hyaloclastics are the primary rocks comprising the Flat Landing Brook Formation. Locally abundant rocks include [[tholeiitic]] to transitional [[mafic]] fragmental rocks and massive flows, as well as [[felsic]] [[tuff]]s, tholeiitic [[pillow basalt]]s and minor [[porphyritic]] felsic flows.<ref name="AK"/> [[Siltstone]], [[greywacke]], [[ironstone|iron formation]], ferromanganiferous [[shale]] and [[chert]] represent minor rocks.<ref name="AK"/><ref name="QW"/>
==Stratigraphy== ===Relationship to other units=== The Flat Landing Brook Formation is the middle member of the Telagouche Group.<ref name="QW"/> Exposures between [[New Brunswick Route 490|Route 490]] and the headwaters of Flat Landing Brook are the [[type locality (geology)|type locality]].<ref name="AK"/> It is conformably overlain by massive pillowed alkali basalt of the Little River Formation and conformably underlain by crystal tuff as well as quartz-feldspar augen schist of the Nepisiguit Falls Formation.<ref name="QW"/> The contact of the Flat Landing Brook and Little River formations is exposed in the Brunswick Mines area and near California Lake whereas the contact of the Flat Landing Brook and Nepisiguit Falls formations is exposed along The Narrows of the Nepisiguit River.<ref name="AK"/>
===Subdivisions=== Four named subdivisions comprise the Flat Landing Brook Formation:
{|class="wikitable" |- ! [[Formation (geology)|Formation]] !! [[Geochronology|Age]] !! [[Lithology]] !! Reference |- | Reids Brook Member || Middle Ordovician || Rhyolite flows, hyaloclastites, breccias |<ref name="AK"/> |- | Forty Mile Brook Member || Middle Ordovician || Tholeiitic pillow basalt |<ref name="AK"/> |- | Roger Brook Member || Middle Ordovician || Tuff and minor porphyritic felsic flows |<ref name="AK"/> |- | Moody Brook Member || Middle Ordovician || Tholeiitic to transitional mafic fragmental rocks and massive flows |<ref name="AK"/> |}
==Volcanology== With an estimated original volume of approximately {{nowrap|{{Convert|12000|km3|mi3|abbr=on}}}}, the Flat Landing Brook Formation is the remains of a [[supervolcano]] similar in size and eruption rates with the [[Lake Taupo|Taupo]] and [[Yellowstone Caldera|Yellowstone]] calderas.<ref name="QB">{{cite web|title=Chemostratigraphy and hydrothermal alteration of the Flat Landing Brook Formation, Brunswick Belt, Bathurst Mining Camp|publisher=[[University of New Brunswick]]|year=2014|last=Wills|first=Alexander Oakley}}</ref><ref name="QL">[http://www.mineralogicalassociation.ca/doc/StJohns2012_GAC-MAC_Abstracts.pdf A mid-Darriwilian super volcano in northern New Brunswick, rapid climate change and the start of the great Ordovician biodiversification event]</ref> It may also represent the largest supervolcanic eruption of the [[Paleozoic]] [[era (geology)|era]].<ref name="QB"/> Most of the volcanics were laid down during a timespan of possibly less than two million years.<ref name="QL"/> A region of coarse volcanic breccias in the Flat Landing Brook Formation is interpreted to be the remnants of a [[caldera]].<ref>[http://ftp.maps.canada.ca/pub/nrcan_rncan/publications/ess_sst/205/205182/cr_1995_e.pdf The petrological variations of the Ordovician felsic volcanic rocks of the Tetagouche Group, New Brunswick]</ref>
